{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599476"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:54:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:54:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15572"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15572"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.1,0,0.14,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8263"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70162"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8263"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55625"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"7593"},{"type":"tags","id":"10475"},{"type":"tags","id":"10481"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19964"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70162"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThyroid hormone synthesis requires the accumulation of iodide within thyroid follicular cells. This process occurs against a concentration gradient, requiring specialised transport mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of iodide uptake into thyroid follicular cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium-iodide symporter driven by calcium gradient","Potassium-iodide symporter driven by potassium gradient","Hydroxide-iodide antiporter driven by pH gradient","Sodium-potassium ATPase driven primary transport","Sodium-iodide symporter driven by sodium gradient"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium-iodide symporter (NIS) is crucial for thyroid hormone synthesis. \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium-iodide symporter driven by sodium gradient\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes how iodide is concentrated in thyroid follicular cells. The NIS uses the energy from the sodium gradient (created by sodium-potassium ATPase) to transport both sodium and iodide into the cell against iodide\u0027s concentration gradient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium-iodide symporter\u003C/strong\u003E does not exist in thyroid cells. While calcium signalling is important in thyroid function, it does not directly drive iodide transport.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epotassium-iodide symporter\u003C/strong\u003E does not exist in thyroid cells. While potassium channels are present, they are not involved in iodide transport.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydroxide-iodide antiporter\u003C/strong\u003E is not involved in thyroid iodide transport. pH gradients do not drive iodide accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium-potassium ATPase\u003C/strong\u003E creates the sodium gradient but does not directly transport iodide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this mechanism is clinically relevant as certain medications (like perchlorate) can inhibit the NIS, and NIS dysfunction can lead to congenital hypothyroidism. The NIS is also important in thyroid cancer treatment, as it allows radioactive iodide uptake for imaging and therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The sodium-iodide symporter (NIS) on thyroid follicular cells actively transports iodide into the cell against its concentration gradient.","The sodium gradient created by the sodium-potassium ATPase provides the energy for iodide transport.","Iodide trapping is the first step in thyroid hormone synthesis and is inhibited by medications like perchlorate."],"references":["Brent GA. Mechanisms of thyroid hormone action. J Clin Invest. 2012 Sep;122(9):3035-43. doi: 10.1172/JCI60047. Epub 2012 Sep 4. PMID: 22945636; PMCID: PMC3433956","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press. USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55625"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15572"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55625"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T20:21:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T20:22:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8263"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70162"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":nu